04800nam a22006735i 9781487575823DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191979onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875758237 a10.3138/97814875758232doi  a(DE-B1597)537021  a(OCoLC)1129181195  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aQC20b.T68 1979eb 7aSCI0510002bisacsh04a530.1/52201 aTrainor, Lynn E.H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFrom Physical Concept to Mathematical Structure :bAn Introduction to Theoretical Physics /cLynn E.H. Trainor, Mark B. Wise. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©1979  a1 online resource (420 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Cartesian tensors and transformation groups -- t3. Rotations, reflections, and more about tensors -- t4. Cartesian tensors at work -- t5. Tensors as a basis of group representations -- t6. Quantum mechanics as a linear theory -- t7. Generalized tensors in Riemannian geometry -- t8. Special relativity -- t9. Classification of elementary particles -- t10. Constructs in Riemannian geometry -- t11. General relativity - an example of a non-linear theory -- t12. Horizons -- tAppendices -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe text takes an innovative approach to theoretical physics. It surveys the field in a way that emphasizes perspective rather than content per se, and identifies certain common threads, both conceptual and methodological, which run through the fabric of the subject today. Starting from recognized physical concepts, it demonstrates how these have led to the mathematical structures used extensively in physical theory and displays the unity of basic physics seen from the viewpoint of the symmetries of nature as manifested in the sensorial properties of physical quantities and physical laws. The text focuses particularly on the linearity principle. A consideration of the description of physical events as viewed from difference reference frames leads on to a discussion of the concepts of tensors and tensor fields as well as the theory of groups and group representations. As the concept of tensors is developed and broadened into multidimensional spaces, examples from elasticity theory, quantum mechanics, and the structure of elementary particles are considered. The nature of linear theories is illustrated repeatedly, but special attention is given to quantum mechanics and special relativity. The text also introduces non-linear geometry, in the sense of both Gauss and Riemann, and considers Riemannian geometry more extensively, as a prelude to a brief introduction to general relativity. The ten main chapters contain references, footnotes, and problems to assist the reader to pursue any topic further. The volume can serve as a text or supplementary text in advanced undergraduate or graduate programs in theoretical physics and should also prove of interest to practicing physicists, mathematicians, and theoretical chemists and biologists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMathematical physics. 7aSCIENCE / Physics / Nuclear.2bisacsh1 aWise, Mark B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148757582340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487575823423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487575823.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MTPY  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_